<paragraph blockId="8.[806,1422,1056,1262]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis box="[806,919,1057,1078]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Variation:</emphasis>
<materialsCitation country="Sudan" location="Red Sea" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" specimenCount="2" stateProvince="Al Bahr al Ahmar">
The 
<specimenCount box="[983,1151,1056,1078]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
from both sides of the 
<collectingRegion box="[806,901,1087,1109]" country="Sudan" name="Al Bahr al Ahmar" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Red Sea</collectingRegion>
, Gabal Elba and Jeddah, are nearly identical. The specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1060,1133,1118,1140]" name="Sudan" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Sudan</collectingCountry>
has slightly shallower sculpture and deeper dorsolateral impressions of the pronotum. The ratio of elytral to pronotal length is constant in the 
<specimenCount box="[1014,1207,1209,1231]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
examined (2.27– 2.29)
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[806,1421,1303,1478]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis box="[806,932,1303,1324]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Etymology:</emphasis>
This species, diffused along the coasts of the Red Sea, is named after Hippalus. He was a Greek navigator and merchant who probably lived in the 1st century BCE, and was credited with discovering the direct route from the Red Sea to 
<collectingCountry box="[1303,1364,1425,1447]" name="India" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">India</collectingCountry>
over the Indian Ocean (Wikipedia contributors, 2008).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[806,1421,1519,1602]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis box="[806,1298,1519,1540]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[963,1056,1519,1540]" captionStart="Figure 108" captionStartId="27.[164,243,1063,1082]" captionTargetBox="[164,1444,196,1033]" captionTargetId="figure-343@27.[164,1444,196,1033]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Figure 108. The Indo-African species of Pachycerus. Distribution map. Map taken from Encarta World Atlas 2000 (Microsoft Corporation), refined with Photoshop 7.0." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443553" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443553/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
): 
<taxonomicName authority="Meregalli, 2009" authorityName="Meregalli" authorityYear="2009" box="[1079,1298,1519,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pachycerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hippali" status="sp. nov.">Pachycerus hippali</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1307,1394,1520,1541]" pageId="8" pageNumber="303" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is present all along the coasts of the 
<collectingRegion box="[1255,1358,1550,1572]" country="Sudan" name="Al Bahr al Ahmar" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Red Sea</collectingRegion>
, and reaches Kurdufan, in central 
<collectingCountry box="[1153,1230,1580,1602]" name="Sudan" pageId="8" pageNumber="303">Sudan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
